  "prompt": "How can you determine the orbital notation of iron?",
  "response": "To determine the orbital notation of iron (Fe), follow these steps:\n\n### 1. **Identify the atomic number of iron:**\n   Iron has an atomic number of **26**, meaning it has 26 electrons.\n\n### 2. **Write the electron configuration using the aufbau principle:**\n   The aufbau principle states that electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing energy. The order is:\n   ```\n   1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, ...\n   ```\n   Follow the rule and distribute the 26 electrons:\n   ```\n   1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u2076\n   ```\n\n### 3. **Draw the orbital notation:**\n   Orbital notation uses arrows (\u2191 or \u2193) to represent electrons in specific orbitals. Each orbital can hold a maximum of 2 electrons with opposite spins. The orbitals are represented as boxes or lines.\n\n   For iron (Fe), the orbital notation is:\n   ```\n   1s: \u2191\u2193  \n   2s: \u2191\u2193  \n   2p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193  \n   3s: \u2191\u2193  \n   3p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193  \n   4s: \u2191\u2193  \n   3d: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191 \u2191\n   ```\n\n### 4. **Explanation of the 3d orbital:**\n   The 3d orbital has 5 sub-orbitals (dxy, dyz, dzx, dx\u00b2-y\u00b2, dz\u00b2). According to Hund's rule, electrons fill orbitals singly before pairing up. For iron, the electrons fill the 3d orbitals as:\n   ```\n   dxy: \u2191\u2193  \n   dyz: \u2191\u2193  \n   dzx: \u2191\u2193  \n   dx\u00b2-y\u00b2: \u2191  \n   dz\u00b2: \u2191\n   ```\n\n### Final Orbital Notation for Iron (Fe):\n```\n1s: \u2191\u2193  \n2s: \u2191\u2193  \n2p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193  \n3s: \u2191\u2193  \n3p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193  \n4s: \u2191\u2193  \n3d: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191 \u2191\n```\n\nThis notation shows how the 26 electrons of iron are distributed among the orbitals.",
